<h2>What Is SEO Visibility Score?</h2>
<h3>The Definition</h3>
<p>SEO visibility score is a percentage-based metric that estimates how much of the total possible organic click opportunity your website captures across a defined set of tracked keywords. It answers one question: of all the clicks available for the keywords you care about, what percentage are you getting?</p>
<p>The score ranges from 0% to 100%. A score of 100% means you rank position 1 for every single keyword you track. This is theoretically possible only if you track one keyword and you own the top spot. In practice, most websites score between 5% and 40%.</p>
<h3>Why Raw Rankings Are Not Enough</h3>
<p>Rankings lie by omission. They treat every keyword equally. Position 1 for "best left-handed guitar picks" counts the same as position 1 for "project management software" even though the second term has 200 times more search volume.</p>
<p>Visibility score fixes this by weighting each ranking by search volume and expected click-through rate. A position 3 ranking on a 20,000-volume keyword contributes more to your visibility score than a position 1 ranking on a 200-volume keyword. This reflects reality. It also means small ranking changes near the top of high-volume terms create outsized visibility swings.</p>
<h3>The Core Formula</h3>
<p>Every tool uses slightly different math, but the underlying logic is consistent:</p>
<pre><code>Visibility Score = Sum of (Estimated CTR × Search Volume) for all keywords
                   ÷ Sum of (Maximum Possible CTR × Search Volume) for all keywords
</code></pre>
<p>In plain terms: you add up the estimated clicks you get from each ranking position. Then you divide by the clicks you would get if you ranked position 1 for every keyword. The result is your visibility percentage.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="SEO visibility score formula explained" src="/images/blog/visibility-score-formula.png" /></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Key insight:</strong> Two websites can rank for the exact same number of keywords and have wildly different visibility scores. The site holding top positions on high-volume commercial terms will dominate. The site ranking on page two for everything will barely register.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>How SEO Visibility Score Is Calculated</h2>
<h3>Position Weights and Expected CTR</h3>
<p>The heart of any visibility calculation is the expected click-through rate for each ranking position. These rates come from aggregate clickstream data across millions of searches. They are not guesses.</p>
