<p>The curve is steep. Positions 1 through 3 capture roughly 60% of all clicks. Position 10 might get 1%. Position 20 gets almost nothing. This non-linear relationship is why a single position jump from 4 to 2 can double your traffic for that keyword while a jump from 15 to 12 changes almost nothing.</p>
<h3>Search Volume as the Multiplier</h3>
<p>Search volume scales everything. A position 2 ranking on a 50,000-monthly-search keyword contributes 50 times more visibility value than the same position on a 1,000-search keyword.</p>
<p>This is where keyword selection becomes critical. Your visibility score is only as good as the keywords you track. A brand tracking 500 long-tail terms with 10 searches each will show a high visibility score that means almost nothing commercially. A competitor tracking 50 high-intent commercial terms will have a lower score that actually drives revenue.</p>
<h3>Normalization to a 0-100% Scale</h3>
<p>After calculating the weighted contribution of each keyword, tools normalize the result. The maximum possible score is ranking position 1 for every tracked keyword. Your actual score is your share of that theoretical maximum.</p>
<p>This normalization makes visibility score intuitive. A score of 25% means you are capturing one quarter of the total click opportunity for your keyword set. It does not mean you rank 25th. It means you are at 25% of maximum possible performance.</p>
<h3>SERP Feature Adjustments</h3>
<p>Modern visibility calculations also account for SERP features that push organic results down. If an AI Overview, featured snippet, or local pack sits above your position 3 ranking, your effective visibility is lower than the raw position suggests. Some tools now factor in pixel position, the actual number of pixels from the top of the page to your listing, rather than just rank number.</p>
