<h2>What Different Tools Measure (And How They Differ)</h2>
<h3>SEMrush Visibility %</h3>
<p>SEMrush calculates visibility as a percentage based on click-through rate estimates multiplied by search volume for your tracked keywords. You define the keyword set. SEMrush refreshes daily.</p>
<p><strong>Key characteristic:</strong> Project-based. You choose which keywords to track. This means your score is highly sensitive to keyword selection. Add 100 low-volume terms and your score jumps artificially. Remove them and it drops.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Agencies and in-house teams who want full control over their keyword portfolio and competitive benchmarking against specific rivals.</p>
<h3>Ahrefs Share of Voice</h3>
<p>Ahrefs does not use a traditional visibility percentage. Instead, it shows "Share of Voice" in Rank Tracker. This metric estimates what percentage of total clicks for your tracked keywords go to your site versus competitors.</p>
<p><strong>Key characteristic:</strong> Focuses on actual estimated clicks rather than theoretical CTR models. Ahrefs also shows "Traffic Potential" to reveal how much more traffic you could capture by reaching position 1 for all tracked terms.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Teams who care about traffic estimates over theoretical position weights. Particularly strong for competitive gap analysis.</p>
<h3>SISTRIX Visibility Index</h3>
<p>SISTRIX uses a fixed keyword set of millions of terms across markets. You do not choose the keywords. The tool calculates visibility based on its own database.</p>
<p><strong>Key characteristic:</strong> Normalized index score, not a percentage. Scores are comparable across websites because everyone is measured against the same keyword universe. A score of 10 in SISTRIX means something concrete relative to other sites in your market.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> European markets where SISTRIX data is deepest. Excellent for historical benchmarking and market-level competitive analysis.</p>
<h3>Advanced Web Ranking (AWR)</h3>
<p>AWR offers multiple visibility metrics including a points-based score, percentage-based score, and pixel-based visibility. The points system assigns 30 points for position 1, scaling down to 1 point for position 30.</p>
<p><strong>Key characteristic:</strong> Pixel position tracking measures actual on-screen placement. With AI Overviews and SERP features pushing results lower, a "position 3" listing might actually appear 800 pixels down the page. AWR captures this.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Teams who want granular technical measurement including actual visual placement on the SERP.</p>
<h3>Google Search Console (Free Method)</h3>
<p>Google Search Console does not calculate a visibility score automatically. But you can derive one using impressions and average position data.</p>
<p><strong>Method:</strong> Export your query report. For each keyword, multiply impressions by average position weight. Sum and normalize against maximum possible impressions.</p>
<p><strong>Limitation:</strong> GSC data is sampled for large sites. It also combines all countries and devices unless you filter aggressively. The "average position" metric can be misleading for keywords where you rank in multiple positions.</p>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Small businesses with limited budgets who need a free baseline.</p>
