<h3>Why Context Matters More Than the Number</h3>
<p>Three factors determine whether your score is good:</p>
<p><strong>1. Industry competitiveness.</strong> A 15% score in personal injury law might put you in the top 10% of firms. The same score in "vintage stamp collecting" might mean you are underperforming.</p>
<p><strong>2. Keyword set composition.</strong> If you track only branded terms, a 90% score is meaningless. If you track only high-intent commercial terms, a 20% score is impressive.</p>
<p><strong>3. Business model.</strong> A local plumber with a 12% visibility score in one city can generate $500,000 in annual revenue. A national SaaS company with the same score might struggle to pay server costs.</p>
<h3>Trend Beats Absolute</h3>
<p>The direction of your visibility score matters more than the number itself. A site moving from 8% to 18% over six months is winning. A site dropping from 35% to 25% is losing ground even though 25% still looks respectable on paper.</p>
<p>Track month-over-month changes. Flag any drop exceeding 10% in a single month for immediate investigation. Algorithm updates, technical issues, or competitor surges can cause sudden shifts.</p>
