<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<p><strong>What is a good SEO visibility score?</strong></p>
<p>A good score depends on your industry and competition. For most small to medium businesses, 15% to 30% represents solid performance. Market leaders in competitive niches might score 35% to 50%. Niche sites with limited competition can exceed 60%. Track your trend month over month rather than obsessing over the absolute number.</p>
<p><strong>How is SEO visibility score different from domain authority?</strong></p>
<p>Domain authority predicts how likely a site is to rank based on backlink profile. Visibility score measures actual performance across your tracked keywords. A site with high domain authority but poor content can have a low visibility score. A site with modest authority but excellent topical content can outperform it.</p>
<p><strong>Can visibility score predict revenue?</strong></p>
<p>Not directly. Visibility score predicts click opportunity. You must layer in conversion rate and average order value to estimate revenue. However, visibility is the most reliable leading indicator of organic traffic growth. If your visibility score trends up for 90 days, traffic will follow.</p>
<p><strong>Why did my visibility score drop after an algorithm update?</strong></p>
<p>Algorithm updates often reshuffle rankings across many keywords simultaneously. A core update might demote your content for certain query types while promoting it for others. Check which specific keywords and pages lost positions. Look for patterns. Did you lose rankings on informational queries? Did commercial terms hold steady? This tells you what to fix.</p>
<p><strong>Should I track branded or non-branded keywords for visibility?</strong></p>
<p>Track both separately. Branded visibility measures brand awareness and reputation. Non-branded visibility measures your SEO effectiveness. A healthy site shows strong non-branded visibility. If branded terms dominate your score, you are either a household name or your SEO is underperforming on commercial queries.</p>
<p><strong>How often should I check my visibility score?</strong></p>
<p>Check weekly for the first three months of a new campaign or after major site changes. Monthly is sufficient for stable, mature sites. Daily checks create noise and anxiety. Visibility moves gradually except during algorithm updates or technical disasters.</p>
<p>Visibility score is the metric that cuts through SEO noise. It tells you whether your rankings actually matter. A high score means you are capturing clicks, not just positions. A rising trend means your strategy is working.</p>
<p>The key is consistency. Track the right keywords in the right tool. Refresh content regularly. Fix technical issues before they cap your potential. And in 2026, start tracking AI visibility alongside traditional SEO visibility. The search surface is splitting. You need eyes on both.</p>
<p>Start measuring today. Pick your tool. Define your keyword set. Record your baseline. Then build a content and optimization plan that pushes your score higher every quarter.</p>
